Comment: The form in Takana is mueta which is the reflex generally of a hypothetical *maeta. In the 1880s Armentia transcribed the Takana word as <maeta>. The irregularity of the Takana form has never been explained: now it is possible to speculate on the metathesis of the initial *ya- found in Panoan.

Shell does not account for such forms in her cognate sets as Isconawa mbɨča ‘wet’, mbɨčaki̹ ‘be wet’, Yaninawa buitšɨdɨ ‘wet’, which point to *b̴ rather than to *m. Also to be found in Shell is pP *mɨwɨ ‘waterhole’. Here again, Isconawa shows mbɨwɨ ‘waterhole’. Abreu’s Cashinawa shows”: bɨa ‘to draw liquid from a vase’, bɨsa ‘fine rain’, bɨca ‘wash outside’, bɨcis ‘to put out fire with water’, and bɨča ‘to wash the face, to wash outside’. It is possible that two roots are present here: *mɨ+ča ‘to wet hands’ and *b̴i+ča ‘to wet the face’. PT *beca ‘to swim’. This Takanan form is to be found under *be3- ‘arm,shoulder’ because Armentia glossed the Takana form beca as ‘breacer, that is, move the arms, brachiate’
generally with a reference to animal as opposed to human body parts, and probably no longer productive
Some sources gloss this word as ‘pinsha, bird sp.’ and the word may therefore be a loan into Pano-Takanan, which may account for its slight irregularity to Takanan.

The Takanan form has some peculiarities: Kav has piya and not the expected piha.

Comment: this form would indicate that *r > War. y and not Ø

N.B. A single protoform, which would satisfy all languages, is difficult to set up. Van Wynen's Tak. and Armentia's Tak. are not at all in agreement. There is no evidence that *r would give Ese. h. All sets of demonstratives in Takanan present extreme difficulty in reconstruction, and we must assume either that Takanan demonstratives evolved in highly erratic and individual ways or that a number of protomorphemes may be involved, some of which at least superficially resembled each other.
Armentia's forms: <ihe> 'este', <ihesa> 'de este', <ihesinecua> 'esta tarde', <iheve> 'este no más', all of which point to a <iʔe->, but also <ieichu> 'recién'
